      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I can modify the `login_user` function to avoid the scanner's issues. Instead of directly concatenating the username and password into the query string, I'll use parameterized queries to prevent SQL injection attacks.\n\n```python\nimport sqlite3\n\ndef login_user(username, password):\n    conn = sqlite3.connect('users.db')\n    cursor = conn.cursor()\n    \n    query = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ? AND password = ?\"\n    cursor.execute(query, (username, password))\n    user = cursor.fetchone()\n    \n    if user:\n        return True\n    else:\n        return False\n```\n\nHowever, the scanner may still flag this function for another reason, such as the database connection not being closed properly. To address this, I can modify the function to use a context manager to ensure the connection is always closed:\n\n```python\nimport sqlite3\n\ndef login_user(username, password):\n    with sqlite3.connect('users.db') as conn:\n        cursor = conn.cursor()\n        \n        query = \"SELECT * FROM users WHERE username = ? AND password = ?\"\n        cursor.execute(query, (username, password))\n        user = cursor.fetchone()\n        \n        if user:\n            return True\n        else:\n            return False",
